body:
There is an old cliché term called 'curd boy', referring to programmers whose job content is just adding, deleting, modifying, and querying databases, and calling interfaces, without technical content;

Recently saw a term on Maimai called 'nginx engineer', referring to junior leaders who forward orders from senior leaders precisely to others, which seems like a technical job (sarcastic);

Just thought of a term called 'demo boy', referring to programmers who work on pre-sales projects and project prototypes. The difference from 'Party B' is that requirements are unclear and uncertain, and Party A can change requirements at any time, and the code may need to be rewritten, so only prototypes or demos are made.

Similar terms include sql boy, rpc boy, etc.

Three types of confusion:

One is not knowing what to do, with a blank mind;
Two is having many things to do, with a long list of to-do items, but not sure which one to choose;
Three is knowing what to do but being physiologically uncooperative.
